  One evening, as the clouds gathered like a mourning crowd, she climbed to the **Peak of the Unspoken**, where the wind spoke in voices. There, she did what no Stormweaver had done in centuries—she **listened**. The storm whispered of forgotten names, of children lost in blizzards, of lovers separated by gales, of travelers who had vanished into the white. It was not rage that drove the wind, but **memory**.

  Mira returned to her loom and wove not with thread, but with **echoes**. She sang the names of the lost into the fabric, stitched the laughter of children into the weft, braided the promises of lovers into the warp. As she worked, the storm outside stilled, pressing against the windows like a curious beast. When she held up the finished cloth—a tapestry of silver and sorrow—it shimmered with faces, voices, lives once forgotten.

  She hung it in the village square, and the storms no longer raged. Instead, they **danced**, swirling around the tapestry as if remembering. The villagers said Mira had tamed the wind, but she knew better. She had not conquered the storm—she had **given it a home**.
